value.value: A rare, autosomal dominant hereditary syndrome characterized by hypercalcemia, abnormally high levels of parathyroid hormone, and isolated hyperfunctioning parathyroid tumors.

A rare, autosomal dominant inherited neoplastic syndrome caused by mutations in the genes that code the succinate dehydrogenase protein complex. It is charcaterized by the presence of gastrointestinal stromal tumors and paragangliomas.

A generalized state of dysregulated inflammation induced by noninfectious processes. It is characterized by two or more of the following signs and symptoms: fever or hypothermia, increased heart rate, increased respiratory rate, and abnormal white blood cell count.
An extremely rare syndrome characterized by the presence of gastrointestinal stromal tumors, pulmonary chondroma, and/or extra-adrenal paraganglioma. There is no evidence of familial inheritance.
The loss of muscle tissue due to inactivity or disease.
Birth of the fetus through the vagina without the application of vacuum or forceps or any other instrument. (adapted from reVITALize)
A group of sleep disorders causing disruption of sleep. Representative examples include nightmare disorders, sleep terror disorders, sleepwalking, and restless leg syndrome.
Leukoplakia of the oral mucosa that is clinically characterized by the presence of erythematous or red and white patches.
A procedure to keep a tissue or organ at body temperature while the blood supply at that site is temporarily decreased or cut off during surgery.
A procedure to keep a tissue or organ cool while the blood supply at that site is temporarily decreased or cut off during surgery.
Loss of a portion of a chromosome arm.
This gene may be involved in neuronal development.

Human ATAT1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 6p21.33 and is approximately 20 kb in length. This allele, which encodes alpha-tubulin N-acetyltransferase 1 protein, may play a role in neuronal development.
Alpha-tubulin N-acetyltransferase 1 (421 aa, ~47 kDa) is encoded by the human ATAT1 gene. This protein is involved in protein acetylation that may be associated with neuronal development.
The documents (e.g., forms, letters, reports) required for a particular activity.
Bringing together multiple scientific disciplines to address specific issues.
Expressed in spoken words.
An assignment to a portion of a study based on a set of criteria that ensures a desired distribution of subjects across all portions of a study.
A description of how a particular amount was assessed.
Terminology used in Individual Case Safety Reports for description of the recipient of a dose.
An area intended to confine animals.
One-fourth of the udder of an animal.
A description of a personal residence and the relationship between the occupants that reside there.

An autoimmune acute encephalitis caused by antibodies against the glutamate NMDA receptor.  It usually affects females and in the majority of cases it is associated with the presence of a tumor, most commonly an ovarian teratoma.  The presence of a tumor in patients with this form of encephalitis implies that the latter is a paraneoplastic syndrome.  It is manifested with psychiatric symptoms and epileptic seizures.  It is a potentially lethal disorder; however, it is usually reversible with the prompt removal of the tumor.
An instrument that uses electric fields to propel charged particles to high speeds and energies.
The amount of radioactivity in a unit.

The time that it takes for an unadulterated administered substance to be reduced by a factor of 2 in its concentration by natural physiological processes. This is entirely separate from any radioactive decay that may or may not be present.
Line through and in the direction of an object's characteristic feature that is longer than any other feature.
Temporal specification associated with a frame. Beginning and ending frame times after the start of injection completely specify an acquisition time.

The original gamma camera invented by H. O. Anger in 1957 and its subsequent generations. This original camera consisted of one large crystal in which gamma rays were converted to scintillations of light. Then, a limited number of detectors viewed these through a collimator to provide an image.
A normalized measure of a difference between 2 quantities, expressed as a percentage difference of either their mean or their sum, whichever is defined by a user.
The fraction of beam intensity being lost per unit length of the transmitting material in a chosen x direction.

Adjustment for the effect of tissue thicknesses through which gamma's travel from an activity concentration origin to the scanner's detectors. The count rates of a detector are adjusted to values as if there were no attenuation along the gamma's path. This makes possible accurate quantitation in image analysis.
The distance along the body axis which can be imaged at one bed position by the scanner's detector geometry.
An electron or positron.
Scan without any subject or attenuating material, but with a source, present.
The volume of blood per unit time passing through a specified location, such as a point in a blood vessel or an entire organ. Units are ml/sec.
The portion of tissue occupied by blood. It is also sometimes expressed for a region as the volume of blood per unit mass of tissue.
One of 47 numbered regions within a map of the cerebral cortex. Each is characterized by a particular cell organization and also corresponds to a particular cortical function.
Perfusion of blood through the cerebrum.
Epilepsy that is refractory to treatment.

A display mode in which the object appears to move due to seeing views from sequentially slightly differing angles. This contrasts with the usual static image display and can assist in visual interpretation.
A plot whose ordinate is a quantifier, such as some measure of activity concentration, at points around an annulus in a slice, and whose abscissa is in degrees.
A table used for interpreting pixels (voxels) to find the correspondence between image intensity values and displayed hues for the particular color scale employed.
A distinct region or state for a particular chemical substance at a cellular level taken to have uniformity throughout but differing from other regions or states.

A physiological model of the kinetics of uptake involving interchanges, such as of an isotope in a tracer, between compartments used to determine rate constants, such as by fitting dynamic scan data to this model.
2 views in planar imaging that are acquired 180 degrees apart around the subject, such as anterior and posterior views.

Pertaining to a plane containing a line parallel to the long axis of the subject's body and in addition presenting anterior and posterior views on each side of it. This plane is perpendicular to both the transaxial and sagittal.
